  | The description states simply "Use Quadlet for running containers and pods under systemd.".<br>tldr: Please tell me how to replace "podman generate systemd" in my environment.<br>In my current setup, I have Podman installed on several hosts, along with podman-compose. The entire setup runs under a rootless user configuration, with all containers operating as rootless as well. I have created a podman-compose.yml file fitting to my use cases and requirements.<br>Once everything is configured properly and the containers are running smoothly with podman-compose, I use the following script to generate systemd service files for the containers created through podman-compose:<br>```<br>#!/bin/bash<br># The directory for systemd user services<br>SYSTEMD_USER_DIR=$HOME/.config/systemd/user<br># Create the systemd user services directory if it doesn't exist<br>mkdir -p "$SYSTEMD_USER_DIR"<br># remove all old entries<br>rm -rf "$HOME"/.config/systemd/user/*<br># Get the names of the running Podman containers<br>CONTAINER_NAMES=$(podman ps -a --format "{{.Names}}")<br># Generate and overwrite the systemd files for each container<br>for CONTAINER_NAME in $CONTAINER_NAMES; do<br>  echo "Generating systemd file for $CONTAINER_NAME"<br>  # Generate the systemd service file for the Podman container<br>  podman generate systemd -t 5 "$CONTAINER_NAME" > "$SYSTEMD_USER_DIR"/"$CONTAINER_NAME".service<br>  # Reload the systemd daemon<br>  systemctl --user daemon-reload<br>  # Enable the new service<br>  systemctl --user enable "$CONTAINER_NAME".service<br>done<br>```<br>I've been using Podman for a long time, especially appreciating the "podman generate systemd" command. The last update seem to move away from this key feature. I checked out Quadlet, but it doesn’t match the functionality and flexibility I'm used to. I don't want to write for every single container a Quadlet file and maintain it.<br>I really like Podman, but the change might force me to consider switching to something else... maybe Docker. I'm open to Quadlet or other alternatives if they can cover the same ground. Is there something I've missed or another way to maintain the functionality I need within Podman's ecosystem? Can I automatically create Quadlet files somehow ? |
  
