  |     |
  | --- |
  | tl;dr<br>- podman is amazing, thank you!!<br>- the primary problem here seems to be the misuse of the word "DEPRECATED", and a subcommand `podman generate systemd -h` shouldn't say "DEPRECATED" if it's not planned to be removed in the forseeable future.<br>- the solution could be to simply remove the word "DEPRECATED" and associated notes from `podman generate -h` and `podman generate systemd -h` outputs.<br>- if it's very important to add a note about this "no new functionality, only bug fixes" in the help messages, those mentions could be replaced with more appropriate language such as "Feature-complete" and/or "Stable/Frozen API".<br>* * *<br>> The current strategy is to deprecate podman generate systemd. That means that no new features will be added to generate systemd but only bug fixes.<br>> there are no plans to remove `generate systemd` as we know and appreciate that it's being widely used<br>the problem here is in the use of the word "DEPRECATED":<br>```<br>$ podman generate systemd -h<br>[DEPRECATED] Generate systemd units<br>...<br>DEPRECATED command:<br>It is recommended to use Quadlets for running containers and pods under systemd.<br>...<br>Please refer to podman-systemd.unit(5) for details.<br>```<br>in every software/program context i've seen the word `DEPRECATED`, it means functionality/API that is promised to be going away or changing, and if you keep using it as-is, it will eventually break in a future update. this necessitates those concerned to figure out the "correct" new way to accomplish the same goal. this means the lucky ones find this discussion in relatively short time and realize they can ignore the word "DEPRECATED" and move on with their lives, while many others spend hours trying to figure out how to adapt to this upcoming change that apparently isn't actually coming.<br>quadlets is confusing and the `podman-systemd.unit(5)` man page says Qualet over and over but never clearly introduces what it is; finding this discussion introduces yet another concept "podlet", bringing an additional confusion. i don't see "one correct way" to replace this command. summarized: it's a perfect recipe for accidentally inducing confusion and wasting time.<br>thanks again! |
  
