  | > I am (quite strictly) against adding a generate-quadlet command. There is already podlet maintained by the community and it works great. Adding it to Podman would mean a lot of duplicated work. Whenever a new feature is being added, it had to be added to multiple places at once.<br>> <br>> I do not want to disqualify the desire of some folks to have such functionality but it is already there with podlet. If users want to use the old generate command, they can use it. As mentioned in the thread, deprecated means that it won't receive new features. But there are not plans to remove it.<br>[@vrothberg](https://github.com/vrothberg) I am glad that podlet exists (TBH I forgot about it and I have it starred on GH already) and I am going to use that to start converting my systemd units that I create with the `podman systemd generate` command.<br>That being said, I can understand from an ease of use standpoint the desire of users wanting to have the features of `podlet` added to Podman. The big problem is that new users to Podman and quadlets have to know that `podlet` is a thing. They don't have to remember that podlet is a thing and have to install yet another binary. Even us Podman veterans forget about all of the different third party tooling available.<br>When I am working on making a new pod with containers I often start with a bash script of `podman run --replace ...` commands so I can quickly iterate on the design of my pod + containers. Using the systemd generate features of Podman make it super easy to create unit files after I have everything in order so I can then transfer those units into my production automation. Just last week I was doing this exact workflow and I thought it would be super neat if I didn't have to RTFM for creating quadlet files to start using them. It is so easy to use `podman systemd generate` and I wished that there was a `podman quadlet generate` command to enable me to use quadlets instead.<br>I totally understand and respect your 